//modulation==number of lines== linedensity
#define linedensity ((1.-(iMouse.x+1.)/iResolution.x))

/*

assuming we have infinite precision, then:
red-green=blue
red-green=blue
red-green=blue
but we do not have infinite precision, but still inherit irrational pi, so the difference is "noise"
That difference is tiny, and amplified by smoothstep() to a point where "yellow" ceases to be noticable.
(best iff paused on time==0)

calculus with short intervals and short wavelengths in general are funny in this asymptotic way.
to a point where you forget that [blue] is a crude neighborhood-loop , while [red-green] is analysis.

blue layer is a laplachian filter; 3 2d neighborhoods (a lot like a common voronoi, but for filtering)
red and green are fwidth() estimates (isoline and zebra scaling)
, to normalize an isoline by dividinf by an estimated first derivative


this allows you to use                fwidth(cos(gradient/pi))   (==Zebra) 
                      or TriangleWave(fwidth(cos(gradient/pi)))  (==Isoline contour)
to approach the asymptotic case of a laplachian 
  (slide mouse to the right to approach asymptote of a [minimal interval of 1px]==[maximum linedensity of 1Line/pixel])
  (that makes the asymptotic case a space-filling case
 , which by definition should appear like a fractal z-order curve, but defined by a (distorting) gradient.

, but the asymptote is approached via calculus+TaylorPolynomials (inherent in fwidth())
for a better understnding of a good hash just being about a low precision epsilon, close to an asymptote.

